<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<chapter xml:id="ch-chords-from-scales" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Building Chords from Scales</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      Any major scale can be used as a source for building chords. By stacking thirds at 
      each scale degree — <term>selecting every other note of the scale above a starting note</term> — 
      we produce a <term>diatonic</term> chord: a chord whose notes all belong to that key.
    </p>
    <p>
      Adding a second stacked third (a fourth note) above the initial triad produces a 
      <term>seventh chord</term>. Seventh chords add harmonic richness and are 
      fundamental to jazz, classical, and popular music. There are exactly seven diatonic 
      seventh chords in every major key — one built on each scale degree.
    </p>
    <p>
      The table below shows the seven diatonic seventh chords built from the C major scale, 
      together with the quality (type) of seventh chord produced at each scale degree.
    </p>

    <tabular halign="center" top="minor" bottom="minor" left="minor" right="minor">
      <col right="minor"/>
      <col right="minor"/>
      <col right="minor"/>
      <col right="minor"/>
      <col/>
      <row header="yes" bottom="medium">
        <cell>Scale Degree</cell>
        <cell>Roman Numeral</cell>
        <cell>Chord</cell>
        <cell>Notes</cell>
        <cell>Quality</cell>
      </row>
      <row>
        <cell>1st — C</cell>
        <cell>I</cell>
        <cell>Cmaj7</cell>
        <cell>C, E, G, B</cell>
        <cell>Major 7th</cell>
      </row>
      <row>
        <cell>2nd — D</cell>
        <cell>II</cell>
        <cell>Dm7</cell>
        <cell>D, F, A, C</cell>
        <cell>Minor 7th</cell>
      </row>
      <row>
        <cell>3rd — E</cell>
        <cell>III</cell>
        <cell>Em7</cell>
        <cell>E, G, B, D</cell>
        <cell>Minor 7th</cell>
      </row>
      <row>
        <cell>4th — F</cell>
        <cell>IV</cell>
        <cell>Fmaj7</cell>
        <cell>F, A, C, E</cell>
        <cell>Major 7th</cell>
      </row>
      <row>
        <cell>5th — G</cell>
        <cell>V</cell>
        <cell>G7</cell>
        <cell>G, B, D, F</cell>
        <cell>Dominant 7th</cell>
      </row>
      <row>
        <cell>6th — A</cell>
        <cell>VI</cell>
        <cell>Am7</cell>
        <cell>A, C, E, G</cell>
        <cell>Minor 7th</cell>
      </row>
      <row bottom="minor">
        <cell>7th — B</cell>
        <cell>VII</cell>
        <cell>Bm7<flat />5</cell>
        <cell>B, D, F, A</cell>
        <cell>Half-Diminished 7th</cell>
      </row>
    </tabular>

    <p>
      Because the chromatic button accordion keyboard is isomorphic, each chord shape is 
      <em>moveable</em>: learn the shape in C and you can play the same chord type from 
      any root button on the keyboard.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <!-- ===================================================== -->
  <section xml:id="sec-diatonic-seventh-chords-cmajor">
    <title>Diatonic Seventh Chords of C Major</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        The grids below show each of the seven diatonic seventh chords of C major in 
        root position. Highlighted buttons are the four chord tones. The final grid 
        shows the full C major scale for reference, making it easy to see how the 
        chord tones are drawn from the scale.
      </p>
    </introduction>

